06475nam a22007455i 9780824856991DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248569917 a10.1515/97808248569912doi  a(DE-B1597)483717  a(OCoLC)1002698355  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBP63.A38bB73 2016 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a297.09592231 aBradley, Francis R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForging Islamic Power and Place :bThe Legacy of Shaykh Daud bin ‘Abd Allah al-Fatani in Mecca and Southeast Asia /cFrancis R. Bradley; ed. by Rita Smith Kipp, David P. Chandler. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSoutheast Asia: Politics, Meaning, and Memory00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tArabic and Jawi Transliteration System -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Rise of the Orangkaya: The Social World of Patani, Thirteenth–Seventeenth Centuries -- t3. The Five Patani-Siam Wars: The Destruction of the Orangkaya -- t4. Meccan Fusion: Patani, Mobility, and Islamic Textualism -- t5. New Power and Authority: Ritual Practice and the Journey of Faith -- t6. Linking Centers: Mecca, Southeast Asia, and the Patani Knowledge Networks -- t7. Institutionalizing Moral Authority: The Making of the Pondok Zone -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aForging Islamic Power and Place charts the nineteenth-century rise of a vast network of Islamic scholars stretching across Southeast Asia and the Indian Ocean to Arabia. Following the political and military collapse of the tiny Sultanate of Patani in what is now southern Thailand and northern Malaysia, a displaced community of scholars led by Shaykh Dā’ūd bin ‘Abd Allāh al-Faṭānī regrouped in Mecca. In the years that followed, al-Faṭānī composed more than forty works that came to form the basis for a new, text-based type of Islamic practice. Via a network of scholars, students, and scribes, al-Faṭānī’s writings made their way back to Southeast Asia, becoming the core texts of emerging pondok (Islamic schools) throughout the region. Islamic scholars thus came to be the primary power brokers in the construction of a new moral community, setting forth an intellectual wave that spurred cultural identity, literacy, and a religious practice that grew ever more central to daily life.In Forging Islamic Power and Place, Francis R. Bradley analyzes the important role of this vibrant Patani knowledge network in the formation of Islamic institutions of learning in Southeast Asia. He makes use of an impressive range of sources, including official colonial documents, traveler accounts, missionary writings, and above all a trove of handwritten manuscripts in Malay and Arabic, what remains of one of the most fertile zones of knowledge production anywhere in the Islamic world at the time. Writing against prevailing notions of Southeast Asia as the passive recipient of the Islamic traditions of the Middle East, Bradley shows how a politically marginalized community engineered its own cultural renaissance via the moral virility of the Islamic scholarly tradition and the power of the written word. He highlights how, in an age of rising colonial power, these knowledge producers moved largely unnoticed and unhindered between Southeast Asia and the Middle East carrying out sweeping cultural and religious change. His focus on Thailand’s so-called “deep south,” which has been marginalized in scholarly studies until recent times, helps lay the groundwork for a new generation of scholarship on the region and furthers our understanding of the present-day crisis in southern Thailand.The study of Islam in Southeast Asia has been most often relegated to the realm of religious studies, and historians have considered the development of the nation as the single-most important historiographical problem in the region. By focusing on the role of human agency and the logistics of knowledge transmission, this book transforms our understanding of the long and complex history of the flow of religious knowledge between the Middle East and Southeast Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIslamzSoutheast AsiaxHistory. 0aMuslim scholarszPatani (Kingdom). 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aChandler, David P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKipp, Rita Smith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485699140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824856991423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824856991.jpg  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK